metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #248
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.

metadata.name: Stitched: Trauma #407
metadata.description:
"Every happy family is alike; every unhappy family is unhappy in its own way." -- Tolstoy

Stitched: trauma is based on the same code, and premise, as Stitched, with one twist: childhood trauma distorts experiences and events; some are wildly chaotic; others obsessively retrace a few curves. It is an experiment in combinatorial complexity: are two mints ever indistinguishable? 

The distortion has been carefully designed to allow a huge space of legibly distinct possibilities.

controls:

mouse click or space bar: pause / unpause / reset animation
s: save current frame
f: toggle between square format and stretch aspect ratio
1-6: set pixel density

metadata.name: Polytone #53
metadata.description:
A graphic poetry between order and chaos.

Voltaire, the philosopher, created the french word « Polytone » to define, in poetry, what is opposed to monotony. This generative work is an attempt to find it in a graphic poetry between order and chaos.

Format: 
Loop 400 frames - 50 FPS - 1000x1000px max. on screen.
By default the loop plays once then stops.

Controls with keyboard :
[p] -> play/pause animation (2 times when loop is off)
[l] -> on/off looping mode
[h] -> switch between 2 stop frames (when loop is off)
[s] -> Export HD capture (8000x8000px) when you want in the loop (only in « Open Live » mode)

Some features with probabilities:
2 colours background : Black (50%) or White (50%)
5 colours palettes : 2 monochrones (45%) or 2 duotones (30%) or 2 composed of 5 colours (25%)
6 pattern types for the image background (16.6% for all)
6 « noise » types : Crosses (26%) or Points (22%) or Line (18%) or Triangle (14%) or Circle (12%) or squad (8%) 
…

metadata.name: Speed of Dark #153
metadata.description:
Simple shapes, when strewn broadly and systematically, suggest the presence of infinite creative possibilities and are capable of portraying a visceral excitement felt by mixing the energy of light with the contemplation of dark.

This exercise has been repeated for ages, and its relevance will remain for as long as light may meet dark. The silhouettes of Stonehenge battling against a bright sky, the wabi-sabi placement of rocks in a Japanese garden hugged by methodical raking, the play of shadows in Plato's Allegory of the Cave, and the playfully arranged cut-outs of collage or chemical photogram — these all attest to the unending dynamism of form when imbued with light and the contrast of its absence.

As absence and darkness are made visible, the trail of their path conveys a speed as fast as light, and dark shapes that are no less important than the brightest figures. A symbiotic coexistence of these forces was born with the universe – and a delicate balance remains between the powerful glare of light and the stealthy speed of dark.

Inspired by photograms and a little-known series by documentary photographer William Klein, Speed of Dark references the visual language of the darkroom and the history of photography as an underlying analog for how an emerging art medium can harness simple elements to create evocative expressions.

Choose a resolution by adding "&width=9000" to the URL in live view.
Remove the border by adding "&noborder=1" to the URL.

May 2022

metadata.name: Inner Stillness #63
metadata.description:
We seek our own inner journeys and Ai is like a waking dream. Images depicting inner worlds, deep collective consciousness. Written in some very ancient language. At least that's what I'm looking for.

Ai render from 1 of my 3D concept art on Artstation.
Examination of color theory through the pixel tile.

Fibonacci tiling of the plane and approximation to Golden Ratio:

Pair 1: 1/1 = 1.000
Pair 2: 2/1 = 2.000
Pair 3: 3/2 = 1.500
Pair 4: 5/3 = 1.6667
Pair 5: 8/5 = 1.6

Workflow:

1- Zbrush + Blender - concept art: 
Sugar Castle: tamasantal.artstation.com/projects/18xW3Z

2- Midjourney: I used this Initial Image as a prompt (link).
I used this render for this fx_hash project: 
NFT from Inner Gardens collection: objkt.com/asset/KT1SwTD9mBy7j8SsCh5StoqtgHwXGnWxZzaW/7 

3- Added pixel patterns: Special pixelation with my own script.

Details: 2000 x 2000 pixels
36 layer - 6 different puzzle picture 
Pixels connected as anti-aliased.

metadata.name: Scaffold #64
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment
